    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-04-27T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-04-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="612"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d612">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.6363 Amiranian/51a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Iran</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-04-27T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 27, 1938—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>28. To be decoded by Engert and to be divulged to no one: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Seaboard Oil Company has informed the Department that it has decided
                            to terminate its concessions in Iran and Afghanistan. Hart<note n="38"
                                xml:id="d612fn38">Charles C. Hart.</note> will proceed to Teheran
                            and Clapp<note n="39" xml:id="d612fn39">Frederick C. Clapp.</note> to
                            Kabul within the next week or two from Baghdad where they now are in
                            order to give the two governments formal notification of the decision.
                            Inasmuch as the decision may cause adverse effects, especially in
                            Teheran, it will probably be necessary for you to remain there until the
                            situation becomes clarified. Bearing in mind the difficulties which
                            Dubois experienced in leaving Iran some years ago at the time the Ulen
                            concession was terminated,<note n="40" xml:id="d612fn40">In October,
                                1932, Arthur W. Dubois, manager of Ulen &amp; Co., was refused an
                                exit visa by the Iranian Government unless he first transferred his
                                power of attorney to another representative. He was granted the visa
                                after a strong protest by the United States.</note> the Department
                            desires you to consider possible ways and means of assisting Amiranian’s
                            American employees in departing from the country in the event that the
                            Iranian Government should attempt to impede their movements.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Referring to your 39, April 25, 1 p.m.,<note n="41" xml:id="d612fn41"
                                >Not printed.</note> these developments will probably obviate the
                            necessity of your consulting at the Department and visiting Kabul.
                            Pending further developments, however, it will be necessary to ask you
                            to defer all plans for leave.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
